	I love button walls but now and then, when saving a siteâ€™s button, I find itâ€™s 88x33 instead of 88x31 and using only the width and height attributes ends up breaking my layout. It seems that browsers follow the height attribute and reduce the width accordingly. I came up with a solution that worked for me (adding a little style) - it may not be the â€™best practiceâ€™ but I decided to share just in case others find it useful: 


	&lt;img src="/images/IMAGENAME.EXTENSION" alt="ALT TEXT" width="88" height="31" style="min-width:88px;max-height:31px;"&gt;


Update 02/13/25: Thanks to Matthew for reminding that using a class name instead of inline styles is probably a better way. In fact, I did that today thanks to his feedback.


I added class="button-fix" to each of the img tags in question and the following to my stylesheet:


.button-fix {
 &nbsp; min-width:88px;
 &nbsp; max-height:31px;
}

It is a better way!

